            'answer' => '{"en":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There are over 40 natural zeolites and as many as 150 synthetic zeolites used today.<\\/p>","pl":"<p>Zeolity s\\u0105 klas\\u0105 minera\\u0142&oacute;w powsta\\u0142\\u0105 w wyniku reakcji chemicznej popio\\u0142u wulkanicznego z wod\\u0105 morsk\\u0105. Maj\\u0105 tr&oacute;jwymiarow\\u0105 krystaliczn\\u0105 struktur\\u0119 otwartych por&oacute;w lub kana\\u0142&oacute;w, kt&oacute;re wygl\\u0105daj\\u0105 jak plaster miodu (lub klatka) i s\\u0105 jednym z niewielu o ujemnie na\\u0142adowanych minera\\u0142ach w przyrodzie. Istnieje ponad 40 naturalnych zeolit&oacute;w i a\\u017c 150 syntetycznych zeolit&oacute;w u\\u017cywanych obecnie.<\\/p>","jp":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There are over 40 natural zeolites and as many as 150 synthetic zeolites used today.<\\/p>","ja":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There are over 40 natural zeolites and as many as 150 synthetic zeolites used today.<\\/p>","es":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There