            155 => 
            array (
                'id' => 168,
                'product_id' => 27,
                'question' => '{"en":"What is a zeolite?","pl":"Co to Zeolite?","jp":"What is a zeolite?","ja":"\\u30bc\\u30aa\\u30e9\\u30a4\\u30c8\\u3068\\u306f\\u4f55\\u3067\\u3059\\u304b\\uff1f","es":"What is a zeolite?","th":"What is a zeolite?"}',
            'answer' => '{"en":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There are over 40 natural zeolites and as many as 150 synthetic zeolites used today.<\\/p>","pl":"<p>Zeolity s\\u0105 klas\\u0105 minera\\u0142&oacute;w powsta\\u0142\\u0105 w wyniku reakcji chemicznej popio\\u0142u wulkanicznego z wod\\u0105 morsk\\u0105. Maj\\u0105 tr&oacute;jwymiarow\\u0105 krystaliczn\\u0105 struktur\\u0119 otwartych por&oacute;w lub kana\\u0142&oacute;w, kt&oacute;re wygl\\u0105daj\\u0105 jak plaster miodu (lub klatka) i s\\u0105 jednym z niewielu o ujemnie na\\u0142adowanych minera\\u0142ach w przyrodzie. Istnieje ponad 40 naturalnych zeolit&oacute;w i a\\u017c 150 syntetycznych zeolit&oacute;w u\\u017cywanych obecnie.<\\/p>","jp":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There are over 40 natural zeolites and as many as 150 synthetic zeolites used today.<\\/p>","ja":"<p>\\u30bc\\u30aa\\u30e9\\u30a4\\u30c8\\u306f\\u3001\\u706b\\u5c71\\u7070\\u3068\\u6d77\\u6c34\\u3068\\u306e\\u5316\\u5b66\\u53cd\\u5fdc\\u306b\\u3088\\u3063\\u3066\\u5f62\\u6210\\u3055\\u308c\\u308b\\u4e00\\u7a2e\\u306e\\u9271\\u7269\\u3067\\u3042\\u308a\\u3001\\u8702\\u306e\\u5de3\\u306e\\u3088\\u3046\\u306a\\u898b\\u305f\\u76ee\\u306e\\u958b\\u6c17\\u5b54\\u306e\\u4e09\\u6b21\\u5143\\u7d50\\u6676\\u69cb\\u9020\\u3092\\u6301\\u3061\\u3001\\u81ea\\u7136\\u754c\\u306e\\u9271\\u7269\\u306e\\u4e2d\\u3067\\u306f\\u8ca0\\u96fb\\u5316\\u306e\\u6570\\u5c11\\u306a\\u3044\\u9271\\u7269\\u306e1\\u3064\\u3067\\u3059\\u3002\\u4eca\\u65e5\\u4f7f\\u7528\\u3055\\u308c\\u3066\\u3044\\u308b\\u5929\\u7136\\u30bc\\u30aa\\u30e9\\u30a4\\u30c8\\u306f40\\u7a2e\\u4ee5\\u4e0a\\u3067\\u3059\\u304c\\u3001\\u3053\\u308c\\u306b\\u5bfe\\u3057\\u3066\\u5408\\u6210\\u30bc\\u30aa\\u30e9\\u30a4\\u30c8\\u306f150\\u7a2e\\u985e\\u306b\\u3082\\u4e0a\\u308a\\u307e\\u3059\\u3002<\\/p>","es":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There are over 40 natural zeolites and as many as 150 synthetic zeolites used today.<\\/p>","th":"<p>Zeolites are a class of mineral formed by the chemical reaction of volcanic ash with seawater. They have a three-dimensional crystalline structure of open pores or channels that looks like a honeycomb (or cage) and are one of the few negatively-charged minerals in nature. There are over 40 natural zeolites and as many as 150 synthetic zeolites used today.<\\/p>"}',
