            'answer' => '{"en":"<p>The porous nature of the zeolite &ldquo;cage&rdquo; and its negative charge, allows for the selective exchange of positively-charged toxins. Inside each zeolite are positively-charged exchangeable (lighter) metals known as cations, usually calcium, magnesium, sodium and potassium.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>These ions are only loosely held and can be readily displaced by other substances, such as toxic heavy metals or other organics in a process called cationic exchange. Zeolites have a preference or affinity for heavy metals due to the positive charge and fit of heavy metals within the zeolite cage.<\\/p>","pl":"<p>Porowaty charakter \\"klatki\\" zeolitowej i jej \\u0142adunku ujemnego pozwala na selektywn\\u0105 wymian\\u0119 dodatnio na\\u0142adowanych toksyn. Wewn\\u0105trz ka\\u017cdego zeolitu znajduj\\u0105 si\\u0119 dodatnio na\\u0142adowane, wymienne (l\\u017cejsze) metale znane jako kationy, zwykle wap\\u0144, magnez, s&oacute;d i potas.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Jony te s\\u0105 tylko lu\\u017ano trzymane i mog\\u0105 by\\u0107 \\u0142atwo przemieszczone przez inne substancje, takie jak toksyczne metale ci\\u0119\\u017ckie lub inne substancje organiczne w procesie zwanym wymian\\u0105 kationow\\u0105. Zeolity maj\\u0105 preferencje lub powinowactwo do metali ci\\u0119\\u017ckich ze wzgl\\u0119du na dodatni \\u0142adunek i dopasowanie metali ci\\u0119\\u017ckich w klatce zeolitowej.<\\/p>","jp":"<p>The porous nature of the zeolite &ldquo;cage&rdquo; and its negative charge, allows for the selective exchange of positively-charged toxins. Inside each zeolite are positively-charged exchangeable (lighter) metals known as cations, usually calcium, magnesium, sodium and potassium. These ions are only loosely held and can be readily displaced by other substances, such as toxic heavy metals or other organics in a process called cationic exchange. Zeolites have a preference or affinity for heavy metals due to the positive charge and fit of heavy metals wi